overview of each mathematical culture and explanatory notes that put each selection into context. This authoritative commentary allows readers to understand the sometimes unfamiliar mathematics of these civilizations and the purpose and significance of each text. Addressing a critical gap in the mathematics literature in English, this book is an essential resource for anyone with at least an undergraduate degree in mathematics who wants to learn about non-Western mathematical developments and how they helped shape and enrich world mathematics. The book is also an indispensable guide for mathematics teachers who want to use non-Western mathematical ideas in the classroom.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 30. Aug 2021) 0aMathematicsxHistoryvSources. 0aMathematics, AncientvSources. 7aMATHEMATICS / History & Philosophy.2bisacsh1 aBerggren, J. Lennart.1 aDauben, Joseph W., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aDauben, Joseph Warren.1 aImhausen, Annette, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aImhausen, Annette.1 aKatz, Victor J., eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aPlofker, Kim, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aPlofker, Kim.1 aRobson, Eleanor, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aRobson, Eleanor.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertPrinceton University Press eBook-Package Backlist 2000-2013z978311044250240uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/9780691235394zCo-access DOI >> click Walter de Gruyter40uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780691235394423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9780691235394.jpg  a978-3-11-044250-2  Princeton University Press eBook-Package Backlist 2000-2013c2000d2013  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_CL_MTPY  aEBA_EBACKALL  aEBA_EBKALL  aE